[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 2H pass 2S pass 3S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "9a4bca5d13f881d1bcf4cbe186a4a068cf8471d78c0718b0704fec0532b1e897"]
[Category "Practice Deals"]
[Difficulty "mixed"]
[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_miscellaneous"]
[Student "S"]
{You open 1\S and partner responds 2\H.

With only 14 points and a 6-card suit you rebid a minimum 2\S. Partner raises to 3\S.

Your bids show 13-15 points. Partner has decided to invite you to bid game with a maximum. Since you have 14 points it's not really clear whether you should accept the invitation. You decide to add a little for your singleton Ace and bid 4\S.

East plays 4\S. South leads the \DK.

<b>East plays 4\S. South leads the \DK.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 2 : \D 2 : \C 0 : Total = 4

The two fast losers in \Hs can't be helped, but maybe you can get rid of one of the \D losers.

Win the \DA and play the \C6 to your \CA. Play \SA, then a small \S to dummy's \SJ. Lead the \CQ. If North covers, ruff and re-enter dummy with a trump so you can discard a \D loser on the \CJ. If North doesn't cover the \CQ when you lead it, discard a \D immediately. As long as North holds the \CK you can make the contract. This is called a Ruffing Finesse.

In some hands there is more than one way to make the conrract.

But in this deal the ruffing finesse is the only Plan that works. }
[Play "W"]DK

